Well, not sure what you mean by "dependent," I guess. It will inherit security from the Polkadot relay chain, which is very robust and obviates the need to secure the chain. It also gains access to interoperability and forkless upgrades.
My assumption is that the team decided it's a net benefit rather than a dependancy, but I can't speak for them.

Bittensor was essentially already it’s own ‘layer one blockchain’ it could operate with or without being attached to Polkadot. ‘Plugging’ into Polkadot just allows for more robust security (since Polkadots infrastructure is so robust and globally distributed and is incredibly decentralized). Seems like Bittensor doesn’t ‘need’ Polkadot. But what Bittensor is crafting will obviously motivate attacks against it (especially when it gets robust enough to properly challenge/shift the paradigm of ‘big money’ and power consolidation within AI). Be thankful the team was wise enough to see the benefits of tapping into Polkadot. View it as Bittensor becoming exceptionally more robust. Plus from a TAO holder’s perspective, the token becomes incredibly portable across chains now.

It’d be a ton harder to ‘shut down’ Polkadot than it would be to ‘shut down’ a fledgling layer 1 like Bittensor. And Bittensor will have a much larger target on its back than standard defi or smart contract platforms. And with Bittensor plugging into Polkadot,  threats (that live outside of bittensors code) will have to threaten the security of Polkadot to have any meaningful impact on the Bittensor network. It’s definitely a smart move.

Hi!

Great question! There does indeed seem to be some misunderstandings on how Bittensor works. 

First, Bittensor is *not* a methodology of unsupervised learning. Bittensor *utilizes* unsupervised learning to perform natural language tasks. The shift from supervised to unsupervised learning for NLP has been a big movement in research as of late, this is because unsupervised learning can identify previously unknown patterns in data and as stated you can get cheaper and more data this way. 

Having said that, this doesn't mean bittensor is limited to unsupervised learning. We built bittensor to be scalable. Part of the reason why we picked NLP and unsupervised learning was to *constrain* the problem into a form we can solve. Once this approach is validated, the aim is to move to other modalities like images, audio, etc using subnetworks of the bittensor network to achieve this, these subnets can work in any way we want them to on, as they're easy to program and build. If someone comes along and wants to build a consensus on supervised learning in a new subnet, they're welcome to.

Finally, supervised learning just means you have the "right answer" when training your model, today models are first trained on unsupervised datasets as a pretraining step and then trained (I.e. fine tuned) with supervised learning to perform a specific task. For example, models that write code are pretrained on the English language and then fine tuned to coding.

The other thing to keep in mind here is that bittensor is going for *generalizability*. You can't get that very well in using only supervised learning since you'll usually create a model that is only good in some number of tasks, instead by using both methodologies you can get a model that generalizes much better
